Even today, clinical medicine largely relies on presenting symptoms and signs that are often out of proportion and are of later stages of the disease. My interest lies in the preclinical window where a subtle molecular change occurs and then translates into a functional shift. As a final-year medico at KMCRI, I firmly believe that the brain is not merely an organ but a complex multimodal system. 



My training at the CSIR–CCMB, Hyderabad, introduced me to molecular approaches in disease research, while my internship at ARTPARK, IISc Bengaluru, demonstrated how structured clinical data fuels AI-driven healthcare innovations. These experiences shifted my perspective from viewing diseases merely as clinical diagnoses to understanding them as complex, multi-layered biological processes.

 

My involvement with brain sciences was further shaped during my neurology elective and participation in various research opportunities hosted by institutes like inStem, NCBS, IISER and NIMHANS—where my work on acute behavioral disturbance received recognition and my interest in neuroscience has been further strengthened through ongoing research on early motor markers of dementia.



Through this internship, I aim to deepen my understanding of early markers and population-level patterns of neurodegenerative diseases and further evolve as a physician-scientist integrating clinical practice and data-driven research.

